  ],
  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The constant oil burning, indicated by adding a quart every 300 miles and blue smoke, especially going uphill, points to oil entering the combustion chambers. The primary suspects are worn internal engine components (piston rings, valve guides, or bearings) or a malfunctioning Positive Crankcase Ventilation (PCV) system. Source 20 explicitly links 'wet, sludgy deposits' on spark plugs to 'Excessive oil entering combustion chamber through worn rings and pistons, excessive clearance between valve guides and stems, or worn or loose bearings.' A restricted or malfunctioning PCV system can also cause excessive oil consumption by pulling oil vapor into the intake or causing crankcase pressure buildup (Source 31, 44, 50). The 'uphill' symptom suggests increased engine load and vacuum fluctuations exacerbating oil pull past worn components.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "The constant oil burning and blue smoke, especially under load, indicates oil is entering the combustion chambers. This is typically caused by worn internal engine components or a malfunctioning crankcase ventilation system. We need to confirm the source. Start by inspecting the spark plugs for direct evidence of oil burning, then check the PCV system.",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "I removed the spark plugs and observed 'wet, sludgy deposits' (Source 20, page 23) on some or all of them.",
    "I checked the PCV valve and it does not rattle when shaken, or there is no vacuum at the hose connection with the engine running. The PCV hoses or oil filler cap are restricted or sludged (Source 50, page 19).",
    "The spark plugs look normal, with no 'wet, sludgy deposits' (Source 20, page 23), and the PCV system appears to be functioning correctly (valve rattles, vacuum present, hoses clear)."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

