  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The symptom of a loud ticking or hissing sound, especially louder when cold and quieting when warm, points to several potential issues. An exhaust leak is a primary suspect, as thermal expansion often seals small leaks as the engine heats up, reducing the noise. A vacuum leak would produce a hissing sound, and could also be more pronounced when cold due to less pliable materials, potentially affecting idle quality. Finally, a noisy hydraulic valve lifter is a classic ticking sound, often louder when cold due to thicker oil or collapsed lifters, and can quiet as oil pressure builds and oil thins. The FSM explicitly details how to diagnose noisy lifters (Source 6, page 20) and mentions intake manifold/carburetor gasket leaks (Source 18, page 47) and exhaust manifold connections (Source 7, page 7) as potential issues.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "A ticking or hissing sound that is louder when cold and quiets when warm can indicate an exhaust leak, a vacuum leak, or a noisy valve lifter. We need to isolate the source of the sound. Perform the following observations and report what you find:",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "I found black soot marks or heard a distinct puffing sound near an exhaust manifold gasket or a crack in the exhaust pipe when the engine was cold.",
    "The engine RPM changed noticeably (either increased or smoothed out) when I sprayed carburetor cleaner or unlit propane around the intake manifold, carburetor base, or a specific vacuum line.",
    "The ticking sound is clearly isolated to the valve cover area of a specific cylinder, and I can feel a shock on the valve spring retainer when the engine is running at idle."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

