  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The symptom of oil weeping down the sides of the engine and a burning smell after driving strongly indicates an external oil leak, likely dripping onto hot exhaust components. The first step is to differentiate between engine oil and transmission fluid, as leaks can be misdiagnosed (Source 4). If it's engine oil, common sources for weeping down the sides and burning include: rocker arm cover leaks, which can flow over the converter housing or seep down the block; oil gallery plug leaks, which flow down the rear face of the block; crankshaft seal leaks, which work back to the flywheel and into the converter housing (Source 4). Additionally, the fuel pump, located on the side of the engine, can leak oil due to a defective diaphragm or mounting gasket (Source 33). An improperly installed or faulty oil filter can also cause leaks (Source 1).",
  "mechanic_instructions": "First, we need to determine if the fluid is engine oil or transmission fluid. Remove the transmission dipstick and note the color of the fluid. Original factory fill transmission fluid is dyed red. Then, visually inspect the engine from top to bottom, paying close attention to the highest point where the leak originates, as gravity will cause it to run down. Look for fresh oil around the rocker arm covers, the fuel pump, the oil filter, and the rear of the engine near the bellhousing.",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "The fluid is red and appears to be leaking from the transmission area (e.g., front pump seal, pan gasket, cooler lines).",
    "The fluid is brown/black (engine oil) and the highest point of the leak is clearly visible around the rocker arm covers.",
    "The fluid is brown/black (engine oil) and the highest point of the leak is clearly visible around the fuel pump on the side of the engine.",
    "The fluid is brown/black (engine oil) and the highest point of the leak is clearly visible around the oil filter housing.",
    "The fluid is brown/black (engine oil) and the highest point of the leak appears to be from the rear of the engine, near the bellhousing or oil pan rear seal."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

