  "diagnostic_reasoning": "A persistent oil leak from the very front of the engine, behind the pulley, points to several common failure points. The primary suspects are the crankshaft front oil seal, the cylinder front cover gasket, and the oil pan front seal, as these components are directly in that area (Source 1, 35, 47, 52, 53, 57). The oil filter, located at the lower left front of the engine, is also a strong candidate for a leak that could appear in this vicinity (Source 42, 51). Finally, the fuel pump, which contains a diaphragm rod seal to prevent engine oil entry, could also be leaking engine oil from its mounting gasket or internal seal (Source 6, 7). The FSM recommends a thorough cleaning and observation to pinpoint the exact source of leakage (Source 1, 29).",
  "mechanic_instructions": "To accurately diagnose this oil leak, we need to pinpoint the exact source. Start by thoroughly cleaning the entire front of the engine, especially around the crankshaft pulley, timing cover, oil pan front, and the oil filter area. Use a suitable non-flammable solvent and blow dry with compressed air. Once clean, add an oil-soluble aniline or fluorescent dye to the engine oil if available, as this can help distinguish engine oil from other fluids (Source 45). Run the engine at fast idle until it reaches normal operating temperature, then raise the car on a hoist and carefully observe the front of the engine for the first signs of leakage. Pay close attention to the areas directly behind the crankshaft pulley, along the cylinder front cover, the oil pan front seal, the oil filter, and the fuel pump.",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "I see oil leaking directly from behind the crankshaft pulley, appearing to come from the crankshaft front seal.",
