  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The milky-brown sludge under the oil cap indicates coolant is mixing with engine oil (Source 11: 'Water formation on the oil level dipstick engine could also be an indication of internal leakage.'). The small bubbles in the radiator when running indicate combustion gases are entering the cooling system (Source 11: 'Internal leakage can be detected by operating the engine at fast idle and looking for the formation of bubbles in the radiator:'). Combined with engine overheating, these symptoms strongly point to a breach in the cylinder head gasket, a cracked cylinder head, or a warped cylinder head/block gasket surface (Source 11: 'Cylinder head gasket defective. Cracked cylinder head or block, or warped cylinder head Or block gasket surface.'). A leaking automatic transmission oil cooler in the radiator is a less likely cause for all three symptoms simultaneously, but it is a possible source of oil in the radiator (Source 11: 'Oil in the radiator may indicate leakage in the block Or leak in the automatic transmission oil cooler:').",
  "mechanic_instructions": "The milky-brown sludge under the oil cap confirms coolant is mixing with your engine oil, and the bubbles in the radiator indicate combustion gases are entering the cooling system. This combination strongly points to a breach in the cylinder head gasket, a cracked cylinder head, or a cracked engine block. To further pinpoint the issue, observe the coolant in the radiator more closely while the engine is running at fast idle.",
